 Philosophy of language explores philosophical questions that arise concerning language. The field includes general theories of lexical semantics, grammatical syntax, and communication as well as formal approaches to meaning in contexts drawn from ordinary discourse, literature, and artificial languages used in logic, mathematics, or science. Major subareas include:

the nature of meaning (see also philosophy of mind); 
the reference of proper names; 
issues arising from natural language grammar (such as those relating to nominal and verbal anaphora);
philosophers' views on the nature of truth (or its equivalents such as "correspondence theory") and how it interacts with language;
the relationship between language and knowledge;
the problem of identifying what counts as coming out true or false when a sentence is applied to the world.[Note 1] In addition there are the various ways in which human psychology and the brain give rise to mental processes which underlie our engagement with language; these include topics like language acquisition, language production and perception, speech acts, information structure, focus, word order/constituent order, the relationship between sounds and meanings, and the role of grammars, among others.

This article takes the view that philosophy of language involves central topics and problems shared by all varieties of human language, whereas linguistic philosophy concerns primarily only Western or Indo-European languages and literatures, though this can be contested. It does not cover applied areas such as stylistics or teaching methods for foreign languages, although many leading applied linguists have published philosophically-informed discussions of their specialisms. There is occasional overlap between the topic matter here and work done within specific linguistic traditions such as structuralism, Chomskyan linguistics, and pragmaticism. Divergence abounds due to differences of emphasis and opinion

